There’s a real principle underneath that.

Reducing internal noise often increases sensitivity to smaller changes in the environment or in your own system.

In practical terms:

* calmer breathing,
* reduced muscular tension,
* less cognitive chatter,
* steadier attention,
* and lower emotional reactivity

can improve detection of subtle differences (“deltas”):

* movement,
* timing,
* recoil,
* tone shifts,
* inconsistencies,
* spatial drift,
* behavioral cues,
* internal state changes.

You see versions of this in:

* shooting,
* tracking,
* meditation,
* surveillance,
* music,
* hunting,
* surgery,
* athletics,
* negotiation.

If your internal signal is turbulent, tiny external signals get masked.

There’s also a predictive-processing angle:
the brain is constantly filtering incoming information. When attention stabilizes, smaller deviations from expectation become easier to detect.

That’s probably part of why stillness can subjectively feel like:

“time slowing down.”

Not literally slower time — but improved temporal resolution and reduced attentional fragmentation.

The same idea transfers into thinking and strategy too:
when you stop reacting impulsively, you can detect:

* second-order effects,
* weak signals,
* hidden assumptions,
* timing windows,
* and structural shifts earlier.

Stillness becomes a way of increasing resolution.